description: From Middle English humorous (compare Medieval Latin hūmorōsus), equivalent to humor +‎ -ous.

adjectives.description: humorous (comparative more humorous, superlative most humorous)

entries.meaning: Full of humor or arousing laughter; funny.
examples: The waiters were so humorous - one even did a backflip for us, when we asked him.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Dependent on or caused by one's humour or mood; capricious, whimsical.
examples: I felt at this time as if I could have been fond of him too, if he would have let me; but I was timid from my childhood, and before long my dread of his displeasure  […]  conquered my humorous inclination to love one who was so handsome, so accomplished, so indulgent and devoted.
